          plot_vector_field3d(F, (x,-3,3), (y,-3,3),(z,-3,3))
        </input>
      </sage>
    </conclusion>
  </exploration>

  <p>
    If someone gives us parametric equations for a curve in the plane, we know how to draw the curve. How do we obtain parametric equations of a given curve? In <xref ref="prob_parametric_curve_in_plane"/>, we were given the parametric equation for the path of a horse, namely <m>x=2\cos t, y=3 \sin t</m> or <m>\vec r(t)=(2\cos t,3\sin t)</m>. From those equations, we drew the path of the horse, and could have written a Cartesian equation for the path. How do we work this in reverse, namely if we had only been given the ellipse <m>\ds\frac{x^2}{4}+\frac{y^2}{9}=1</m>, could we have obtained parametric equations <m>\vec r(t)=(x(t),y(t))</m> for the curve?
  </p>

