  <p>
    If someone gives us parametric equations for a surface, we can draw the surface. This is what we did in <xref ref="prob_parametric_surface_example"/> and <xref ref="second_parametric_surface_example"/>.
    How do we work backwards and obtain parametric equations for a given surface?
    This requires that we write an equation for <m>x</m>, <m>y</m>, and <m>z</m> in terms of two input variables (See <xref ref="prob_parametric_surface_example"/> and <xref ref="second_parametric_surface_example"/> for examples).
    In vector form, we need a function <m>\vec r\colon \mathbb{R}^2\to\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
    We can often use a coordinate transformation <m>\vec T\colon \mathbb{R}^3\to\mathbb{R}^3</m> to obtain a parametrization of a surface.
  </p>

  <p>
    The next three problems show how to do this.
  </p>

