  <exploration xml:id="x3d_parametric_plot">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Consider the surface <m>z=9-x^2-y^2</m> plotted in <xref ref="prob_3dsurface_plot"/>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Using the rectangular coordinate transformation <m>\vec T(x,y,z)=(x,y,z)</m>, give a parametrization <m>\vec r\colon \mathbb{R}^2\to\mathbb{R}^3</m> of the surface. 

          This is the same as saying
          <me>
            x=x, y=y, z=?.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Use the surface equation to eliminate the input variable <m>z</m> in <m>T</m>.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </task>
    <task>
      <p>
        What bounds must you place on <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> to obtain the portion of the surface above the plane <m>z=0</m>?
      </p>
    </task>
    <task xml:id="general_param_3d">
      <p>
        If <m>z=f(x,y)</m> is any surface, give a parametrization of the surface (i.e., <m>x=?, y=?, z=?</m> or <m>\vec r (?,?)=(?,?,?)</m>.)
      </p>
    </task>
    <conclusion>
      <p>
        Use <url href="http://wolfr.am/zk2KTu">Wolfram Alpha</url> or the SageMath cell below to plot the parameterizations.
      </p>
      <sage>
        <!-- <url href="http://aleph.sagemath.org/?z=eJwL0ajQqdSp0lSwVYCyuAqKMvNKFJRCNKpsK7QrNRUyi5V0FGA8roLEosTc1JKizOT4gpz8Eg2YhA5Iv66xjjGIVQlhaQIALhka5w">Sage</url> -->
